(chapter
  :book \"book-of-motion\"
  :number 19
  :title \"Keyframes, In-Betweens, and Timing Charts\"
  :short-title \"keyframes-and-inbetweens\"
  :estimated-words 3400
  :philosopher-weave (aristotle wittgenstein-late peirce)

  :prose
\"Animation on paper (or, today, on a computer) is built out of a small vocabulary of drawing types. Once you know the vocabulary, you can look at any animator's rough drawings and understand what they were planning. This chapter is the vocabulary.

There are three kinds of drawings, and they exist in relation to each other. **Keys** define the extremes of a motion. **In-betweens** fill in the frames between keys. **Timing charts** tell the in-betweener how the frames are spaced. Any animated scene, from a Termite Terrace short to a Ghibli feature, is built out of keys and in-betweens spaced according to timing charts.

# The key drawing

A key is the drawing that captures a moment of pose — one of the extreme positions in a motion. If a character is throwing a ball, the keys of that motion are: the starting stance, the wind-up (arm back, weight shifted), the release (arm forward, weight forward, ball just leaving hand), and the follow-through (arm across the body). Four keys, four moments the animator chooses because they define the shape of the whole throw.

Keys are where the animator does the most important thinking. The key drawings are what will make the audience feel weight, timing, and character. If the keys are boring — if they all look the same, or if they are staged unclearly — no amount of skilled in-betweening will save the scene. If the keys are good, even relatively simple in-betweening will produce a scene that feels alive.

Preston Blair, in his 1949 book *Advanced Animation*, laid out the pose-to-pose approach in detail. He drew example after example of key poses — a walk cycle in eight keys, a run cycle in six keys, a jump in five keys — with careful attention to how each pose captured a specific moment of weight distribution. His diagrams are still standard reference material in animation schools today.

# The in-between

An in-between is a drawing that lies between two keys. Its job is to complete the motion — to take the character from the position of the first key to the position of the second key in a way that feels continuous.

In-betweens are technical work. They require careful attention to shape volumes (the character's body should be the same three-dimensional object in every frame), to line quality (the drawing style should stay consistent), and to arc (the path of each part of the body from key to key should be a natural curve, not a straight line). Studio animation traditionally divided the work: senior animators drew the keys, and less senior artists — often called *in-betweeners* or *assistant animators* — drew the in-betweens. This division of labor made large productions feasible.

# The timing chart

The timing chart is a diagram — usually a small drawing next to a key — that tells the in-betweener how many in-betweens to draw between one key and the next, and how those in-betweens should be spaced.

The simplest timing chart is a straight line with tick marks: if there are eleven in-betweens between two keys spaced evenly, that's a straight line with eleven equal divisions. This gives constant-velocity motion — the character moves the same distance frame after frame.

But most animation is not constant-velocity. Slow-in and slow-out (one of the twelve principles) means motion accelerates and decelerates. To draw a slow-in, the in-betweens near the second key are packed closer together (small distances between frames = slow motion), and the in-betweens near the first key are spread further apart (large distances between frames = fast motion). The timing chart for a slow-in looks like a line with tick marks that get closer together as they approach one end.

There are named timing patterns that animators use often. **Ease-out** means the motion starts slow and speeds up (tick marks that get further apart). **Ease-in** means the motion starts fast and slows down (tick marks that get closer together). **Ease-in-out** means slow-fast-slow. **Cushioned** means slow-in on both sides.

The timing chart is a compact language. An animator can hand a page of keys to an in-betweener along with timing charts for each key-to-key interval, and the in-betweener can produce all the required drawings without further instruction. This is what let the studio system scale.

# What we can do in Scheme

Let's build a small demonstration of a motion with keys, in-betweens, and a timing chart.

```scheme
;; Two keys of a horizontal motion.
;; Key 1: figure at x=100, y=200
;; Key 2: figure at x=500, y=200
;; Number of frames between the keys: 11 (giving 12 frames total: key1 + 11 in-betweens + key2)

;; A timing chart is a list of fractions between 0 and 1 representing
;; the progress at each frame. A linear chart is (0/11, 1/11, ... 11/11).
;; A cushioned chart uses non-linear spacing.

(define (linear-chart n)
  (map (lambda (i) (/ i n)) (range 0 (+ n 1))))

;; An ease-in-out chart: use a sigmoid-like curve
;; s-curve maps 0-1 to 0-1 with slow start and slow end
(define (s-curve x)
  ;; smoothstep: 3x^2 - 2x^3
  (- (* 3 x x) (* 2 x x x)))

(define (ease-in-out-chart n)
  (map (lambda (i) (s-curve (/ i n))) (range 0 (+ n 1))))

;; A very slow-in chart: cube the progress
(define (slow-in-chart n)
  (map (lambda (i) (expt (/ i n) 3)) (range 0 (+ n 1))))

;; Given a chart, produce the position at each frame
(define (positions-from-chart chart x1 x2)
  (map (lambda (t) (+ x1 (* t (- x2 x1)))) chart))

;; Compare three motions of the same start and end points:
;; linear, ease-in-out, slow-in.
(define linear-motion    (positions-from-chart (linear-chart 11) 100 500))
(define eased-motion     (positions-from-chart (ease-in-out-chart 11) 100 500))
(define slow-in-motion   (positions-from-chart (slow-in-chart 11) 100 500))

;; linear-motion:    (100 136 173 209 245 281 318 354 390 427 463 500)
;; eased-motion:     (100 100 111 141 189 245 302 355 400 431 452 500)
;; slow-in-motion:   (100 100 100 101 106 118 141 178 235 313 415 500)
```

The three lists show what happens with the same two keys but different timing charts. The linear motion moves the same distance every frame. The eased motion moves slowly near both ends and quickly in the middle — the character seems to accelerate away from the first key and decelerate into the second. The slow-in motion is dramatic: the character barely moves for the first several frames, then accelerates enormously, arriving at the second key at high speed.

If you played these three motions side by side, they would look different. The linear one would feel mechanical. The eased one would feel natural. The slow-in one would feel *tense* — like the character was building up to a lunge.

# Extreme, breakdown, in-between

Inside the vocabulary of studio animation, there is a further subdivision. The **extreme** drawings are the outermost keys of a motion — the most extended, most contorted, most decisive positions. A **breakdown** is a drawing between two extremes that isn't a straight in-between but is chosen deliberately to shape the arc of the motion — a specific transitional pose that adds character.

For example, if a character punches, the extreme drawings are the wind-up (arm all the way back) and the impact (arm all the way forward). A breakdown might be the moment the arm is halfway forward but the wrist has snapped into position — the wrist leads the fist. The breakdown isn't in either extreme, but it defines how the wrist and hand transition between them.

Studio animation of the highest quality tends to use extremes plus breakdowns plus in-betweens, giving the animator control over three levels of the motion. Less careful animation uses only extremes and in-betweens, which produces motion that reads as competent but not exceptional.

# On the twos

There is one more timing decision that most studio animation makes and that beginners often don't notice: whether the animation runs *on ones* or *on twos*.

A film runs at twenty-four frames per second. If every frame is a new drawing, we say the animation is on ones. If each drawing is photographed twice, so the same drawing shows for two frames in a row, we say the animation is on twos. Animation on twos runs at effectively twelve drawings per second — half the drawing labor.

Most studio character animation from the golden era is on twos. The exceptions are fast, snappy motion — an eye blink, a hand gesture — which is often on ones because at twelve drawings per second the motion would look choppy. Very slow, sustained motion — a character breathing, a scene establishing — can be on threes or even fours (each drawing held for three or four frames), because at very slow speeds the human eye doesn't need many drawings per second to see continuous motion.

Modern hand-drawn animation and 3D animation still make these decisions. A 3D animator will set keyframes and let the software interpolate; the software runs on ones (a new pose per frame), but the animator can go in and modify individual frames to give the motion the character of on-twos. Ghibli films, notably, animate character action on ones or twos depending on the scene, and Miyazaki has been known to redraw scenes that were animated on twos to run on ones if he felt the motion needed the extra smoothness.

# What the vocabulary lets you do

Once you have the vocabulary — keys, in-betweens, timing charts, extremes, breakdowns, ones/twos — you can plan and analyze animation with precision. You can look at a scene and identify where the keys are, how the timing is shaped, whether the animation is on ones or twos. You can hand your plans to someone else — an in-betweener, a colleague, a rendering pipeline — with enough specificity that they can produce what you have designed.

This is the same as any technical vocabulary. Once you have it, you can share your ideas with other people who share it. The vocabulary is what lets a group of animators produce a coherent film together.

# What to notice in a scene

When you watch an animated scene closely, look for:

Where the keys are. Which drawings look like they carry the character of the motion — the extended pose, the strongly-shaped moment. Those are the keys.

How the in-betweens are timed. Does the motion feel constant-velocity, or does it accelerate and decelerate? Are there moments where the character seems to hesitate before a big movement (a slow-in) or overshoots and comes back (a follow-through)?

Whether it's on ones or twos. On a screen, look at a slow-moving character and count the frames per new pose. If each pose lasts two frames, it's on twos.

Where the breakdowns are. In the middle of a fast motion, is there a moment where the character passes through an unusual transitional pose — a wrist snap, a foot flick, a shoulder shrug? Those are the breakdowns.

These are the physical decisions that make the difference between animation that reads as *life* and animation that reads as *movement*. Life is the goal.

# Sources cited

Frank Thomas and Ollie Johnston, *The Illusion of Life: Disney Animation* (Abbeville Press, 1981). Chapters on planning and drawing.

Richard Williams, *The Animator's Survival Kit* (Faber, 2001). The most complete modern textbook on character animation technique. Williams (1933-2019) was a working animator (studio-independent, most known for directing *Who Framed Roger Rabbit* animation, 1988) and his book is used in most animation schools.

Preston Blair, *Advanced Animation* (Foster Publications, 1949; various later editions). The classic text on pose-to-pose animation, illustrated with detailed key poses.

Ollie Johnston and Frank Thomas, *The Illusion of Life: Disney Animation* (Abbeville, 1981).\"

  :notes
\"Named individuals (Blair, Williams, Thomas, Johnston) and their books are all real and widely used in animation instruction. The vocabulary described (keys, in-betweens, timing charts, extremes, breakdowns, ones/twos) is standard animation industry vocabulary and can be verified in any of the cited books. Ghibli attribution for on-ones-versus-on-twos is a widely-reported studio practice; specific Miyazaki redraw-for-ones anecdotes are discussed in various making-of documentaries and interviews. Corporate name-drops kept minimal: 'Ghibli' as movement, 'Termite Terrace' as historical location.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Aristotle: keys as the extremes that define the shape of an action, in-betweens as the substance connecting the extremes.
Wittgenstein-late: the vocabulary as shared language-game — animators use these words with each other because they have learned the practice together.
Peirce: the timing chart as symbol — a written convention that specifies motion behavior in a form the in-betweener can read.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Chapter 20 takes timing further — how the same motion in different timing communicates different emotions, and why a shrug can be sad or funny depending on how long it takes.\")
")
